te-Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1035–1082":"1035–1082","1016–1082":"1016–1082","1035–Female":"1035–Deceased","1031–Male":"1031–Deceased","1065–1118":"1065–1118","1070–1123":"1070–1123","0984–1036":"0984–1036","1000–Female":"1000–Deceased","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1065":"1065","1031":"1031","Cir 1065":"1065","1082":"1082","1070":"1070","1118":"1118","0984":"0984","1016":"1016","1036":"1036","1025":"1025","1035":"1035","1123":"1123","Abt 1070":"about 1070","ABT 1061":"about 1061","Dieppe, Normandy, France":"Dieppe, Normandy, France","Dieppe, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France":"Dieppe, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France","Blandford, Dorset, England":"Blandford, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","France":"France","Saint-Clair-d'Arcey, Eure, Normandy, France":"Saint-Clair-d'Arcey, Eure, Upper Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Court","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic or occupational name from Middle English <i>curt</i>, <i>court</i> ‘large house’ (a word of the same ultimately Latin origin as 2 below), denoting someone who lived or worked in a manor house or castle, a courtly retainer.","French: topographic name from Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (from Latin <i>cohors</i>, <i>cors</i>, genitive <i>cohortis</i>, <i>cortis</i> ‘court, farmyard, enclosure’).","English and French: nickname for a physically small man, or ironically for a large man, from the adjective Middle English <i>curt</i>, Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘short, small’ (from Latin <i>curtus</i> ‘curtailed, truncated, cut short, broken off’). Compare French   Lecourt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Courtade","meanings":["French (mainly southern): topographic name derived from Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (see   Court  ), or a habitational name from (La) Courtade, the name of several places in the southwestern part of France."]},{"name":"Cournoyer","meanings":["French Canadian: topographic name for someone living at a farm with a walnut tree in the farmyard, from French <i>cour(t)</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (see   Court  ) + <i>noyer</i> ‘walnut tree’. Compare   Courneya  .","History: This surname was originally a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne Pierre Hus <i>dit</i> Cournoyer from QC (a son of Paul Hus from Montigny in Seine-Maritime, France; see   Hus  ), who married Jeanne Vanet in QC in 1700. His descendants also bear altered forms of the former secondary surname, such as <i>Courneya</i>, and also the surname   Paulette  ."]},{"name":"Curt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Frieda.","English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Court  .","Americanized form of German   Kurt  ."]},{"name":"Curtis","meanings":["English: nickname for a refined person, sometimes perhaps given ironically, from Middle English, Old French <i>courteis</i>, <i>courtois</i>, <i>curtis</i> ‘courtly, refined, urbane’ (derivative of Old French <i>court</i>; see   Court   1)."]},{"name":"Lecourt","meanings":["French: nickname for a physically small man (or ironically for a large man), a variant of   Court  , with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>."]},{"name":"Courtemanche","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Amedee, Andre, Armand, Fernand, Herve, Lucien, Marcel, Normand, Ovide, Raoul.","French: habitational name from Courtemanche or Courdemanche, the name of several places in Somme, Sarthe, Eure, and Orne, derived from Latin <i>cortis dominica</i> ‘lord's farm or estate’ (see   Court  ). Compare   Shortsleeve  .","History: Antoine Courtemanche <i>dit</i> Jolicoeur from Bannes in Sarthe, France, married Élisabeth Haquin in Montreal, QC, in 1663."]},{"name":"Courtier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Patrice.","French: habitational name from any of the places called Courtier (Seine-et-Marne, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence) or Courtière (Loir-et-Cher).","French: occupational name or perhaps a nickname from Old French <i>courtier</i> ‘arbitrator, judge’."]},{"name":"Cort","meanings":["Catalan: from <i>cort</i> ‘court’ (from Latin <i>cohors</i>, <i>cors</i>, genitive <i>cohortis</i>, <i>cortis</i> ‘court, farmyard, enclosure’), an occupational name for someone who worked in a manorial court or a topographic name for someone who lived in or by one.","English: variant of   Court  .","Americanized form of Dutch, German, and Jewish   Kort  ."]},{"name":"Courchesne","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Aime, Andre, Aurel, Emile, Gaston, Germain, Gilles, Jean-Claude, Marcel, Marcelle.","French Canadian: topographic name for someone living at a farm with an oak tree in the farmyard, from (Old) French <i>cour(t)</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (see   Court  ) + Old French <i>chesne</i> (French <i>chêne</i>) ‘oak’. Compare   Courchaine  ."]},{"name":"Courts","meanings":["English: variant of   Court  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Americanized form of German   Kurtz   or its Dutch cognate <b>Koerts</b>."]}]},{"name":"Adelina","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Adeline  , which has enjoyed some favour in the English-speaking world. It was famously borne by the Spanish-born opera singer  Adelina Pattie  (  1843–1919 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705181,"age":0,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705182,"age":31,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Adelina A Court was born in 1035, in Lincolnshire, England, her father, John A. Court, was 51 and her mother, Adelina Marie de Riddlesford, was 35. She married Norman d’Arcy about 1061, in Dieppe, Normandy, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1082, in Dieppe, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1035–1082":"1035–1082","1016–1082":"1016–1082","1035–Female":"1035–Surnud","1031–Male":"1031–Surnud","1065–1118":"1065–1118","1070–1123":"1070–1123","0984–1036":"0984–1036","1000–Female":"1000–Surnud","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1065":"1065","1031":"1031","Cir 1065":"1065","1082":"1082","1070":"1070","1118":"1118","0984":"0984","1016":"1016","1036":"1036","1025":"1025","1035":"1035","1123":"1123","Abt 1070":"umbes 1070","ABT 1061":"umbes 1061","Dieppe, Normandy, France":"Dieppe, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Dieppe, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France":"Dieppe, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Blandford, Dorset, England":"Blandford, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","France":"Prantsusmaa","Saint-Clair-d'Arcey, Eure, Normandy, France":"Saint-Clair-d'Arcey, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1035–1082":"1035–1082","1016–1082":"1016–1082","1035–Female":"1035–Kuollut","1031–Male":"1031–Kuollut","1065–1118":"1065–1118","1070–1123":"1070–1123","0984–1036":"0984–1036","1000–Female":"1000–Kuollut","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1065":"1065","1031":"1031","Cir 1065":"1065","1082":"1082","1070":"1070","1118":"1118","0984":"0984","1016":"1016","1036":"1036","1025":"1025","